of exposure alone","Both concentration gradient and duration of exposure","Neither concentration nor duration of exposure","Random molecular distribution"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring limb development, \u003Cstrong\u003Eboth concentration gradient and duration of exposure to Sonic hedgehog (Shh)\u003C/strong\u003E are crucial for determining digit identity. Higher concentrations and longer exposure times result in more posterior digit identities (e.g. digit 5), while lower concentrations and shorter exposure times lead to more anterior digits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentration gradient alone\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient - both the level and timing of Shh exposure are necessary for proper digit specification\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuration of exposure alone\u003C/strong\u003E cannot explain the complete patterning - the concentration gradient is also essential\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeither concentration nor duration of exposure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as both factors are well-established determinants\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom molecular distribution\u003C/strong\u003E would not result in the precise and consistent digit patterns observed in normal development\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis dual requirement for both concentration and timing ensures proper digit number and identity during limb development.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sonic hedgehog protein controls digit identity and number through both its concentration gradient and duration of exposure.","Higher concentrations and longer exposure to Sonic hedgehog result in more posterior digit identities."],"references":["Scherz PJ, McGlinn E, Nissim S, Tabin CJ. Extended exposure to Sonic hedgehog is required for patterning the posterior digits of the vertebrate limb. Dev Biol. 2007 Aug 15;308(2):343-54. doi: 10.1016/j.ydbio.2007.05.030. Epub 2007 May 31. PMID: 17610861; PMCID: PMC2100419.","Bouldin CM, Gritli-Linde A, Ahn S, Harfe BD. Shh pathway activation is present and required within the vertebrate limb bud apical ectodermal ridge for normal autopod patterning. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2010 Mar 23;107(12):5489-94. doi: 10.1073/pnas.0912818107. Epub 2010 Mar 8. PMID: 20212115; PMCID: PMC2851812.","Suzuki T. How is digit identity determined during limb development? Dev Growth Differ. 2013 Jan;55(1):130-8. doi: 10.1111/dgd.12022. Epub 2012 Dec 12. PMID: 23230964."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59366"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16016"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/59366"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-24T07:40:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-24T07:40:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8707"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"ty